ch</a>: and using police intimidation to compel these creators to delete th=
eir code repositories is as serious a violation of human rights law as comp=
elling a writer to burn his or her own books.</p><p style=3D"margin:0.5em 0=
px 1.3em;padding:0px;border:0px;font-family:inherit;font-size:inherit;font-=
style:inherit;font-variant:inherit;font-stretch:inherit;line-height:21px">I=
t=E2=80=99s also as ultimately futile: while the Chinese authorities have c=
hosen to target and disrupt two centralised stores of code, thousand of for=
ked copies of the same software exist=E2=80=94both on other accounts on Git=
hub and in private copies around the Net. ShadowSocks and GoAgent represent=
 hours of creative work for their authors, but the principle behind them is=
 reproducible by many other coders. The Great Firewall may be growing more =
sophisticated in detecting and blocking new circumvention systems, but even=
 as it does so, so new code blossoms.</p><p style=3D"margin:0.5em 0px 1.3em=
;padding:0px;border:0px;font-family:inherit;font-size:inherit;font-style:in=
herit;font-variant:inherit;font-stretch:inherit;line-height:21px">Meanwhile=
 the intimidation of programmers remains a violation of the human rights of=
 the coder=E2=80=94and a blow to the rights of everyone who relies on their=
 creativity to exercise their own rights.</p></div></div></div></div></div>=
